SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 925
By Stevens
A RESOLUTION to honor and commend Charles A. "Charlie"
Trost upon the occasion of his thirty years of
service as a Uniform Law Commissioner for the
State of Tennessee.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly are pleased to recognize those
distinguished citizens whose professional achievements and public service have greatly
benefited the citizens of this State; and
WHEREAS, one such noteworthy individual is Charles A. "Charlie" Trost, who has
distinguished himself as a professional of the greatest dedication, ability, and integrity; and
WHEREAS, born on January 6, 1938, Charlie Trost served honorably in the United
States Army Reserve after enlisting in 1957 and volunteered for active duty in Taipei, Taiwan,
during the Second Taiwan Strait Crisis; he later continued his service in the Army Reserve and
received an honorable discharge in 1963, having earned the Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal
for his participation in military operations abroad; and
WHEREAS, after completing his legal education, Mr. Trost began a distinguished legal
career that included service as a law clerk to the Honorable William E. Miller, Chief Judge of the
United States District Court for the Middle District of Tennessee, followed by the practice of law
in Columbia, Tennessee, where he quickly became known for his dedication to clients and his
willingness to provide pro bono legal representation in criminal cases; and
WHEREAS, he also served with distinction on the Tennessee Law Revision
Commission, where he chaired the committee responsible for drafting the Tennessee Criminal
Code and Code of Criminal Procedure, legislation that helped modernize and strengthen the
State's legal framework; and
SJR0925
015379
- 1 -

WHEREAS, Charlie Trost furthered his legal education through graduate study in the
New York University School of Law Graduate Tax Program before continuing his career in
private practice, ultimately joining the Nashville law firm of Waller Lansden Dortch & Davis,
where he served as a partner and later as Senior Counsel and became widely respected for his
knowledge of tax law and public finance; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Trost's reputation for legal acumen and public service led to his
appointment as Commissioner of Revenue for the State of Tennessee in 2010, during which
time he provided steady leadership to the department responsible for the administration of
Tennessee's tax laws and the collection of revenues that support essential public services; and
WHEREAS, throughout his distinguished legal career, Charlie Trost has contributed to
numerous economic development initiatives that have strengthened Tennessee's economy,
providing legal counsel and guidance in connection with projects involving major employers,
such as Nissan, Saturn, Bridgestone, and HCA, thereby helping foster job creation and
economic growth across the State; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Trost has also been deeply involved in civic and professional
organizations, serving in leadership roles with the Maury County Library Board, the Maury
County Hospital Board, the Maury County Mental Health Association, the Maury County Bar
Association, and other organizations devoted to improving the quality of life for Tennesseans;
and
WHEREAS, in recognition of his expertise and integrity, Charlie Trost was appointed by
Governor Don Sundquist in 1997 to serve as a Uniform Law Commissioner for the State of
Tennessee, becoming a member of the National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform
State Laws, now known as the Uniform Law Commission, an organization dedicated to drafting
model legislation to promote clarity and uniformity among the states; and
- 2 - 015379

WHEREAS, during his thirty years of service as a Tennessee Uniform Law
Commissioner, Mr. Trost has contributed his knowledge and experience to numerous drafting
and study committees and has played an important role in shaping legislation that has
strengthened the legal systems of Tennessee and other states; and
WHEREAS, among his most notable contributions was his work as Reporter and Drafter
for the Revised Uniform Unclaimed Property Act, legislation designed to improve the
administration of unclaimed property laws and assist states in returning millions of dollars in
unclaimed assets to their rightful owners; and
WHEREAS, through his many years of distinguished service to the legal profession and
the people of this State, Charlie Trost has exemplified the highest standards of professionalism,
integrity, and public service; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that this General Assembly pause in its deliberations to recognize
Mr. Trost for his many contributions to the law and for his exemplary service as a Uniform Law
Commissioner for the State of Tennessee; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor and commend Charles A. "Charlie" Trost
upon the occasion of his thirty years of distinguished service as a Uniform Law Commissioner
for the State of Tennessee and extend to him our best wishes for continued success and
happiness in all his future endeavors.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
